    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>) [Glenridding House, Patterdale.]</placeName>
                    <date>June 17<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1881</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged to you for so kindly pointing out the error into which I have fallen, &amp; which I will correct, sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. there ever be a new edition of my little book on Expression.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>I remain, dear Sir, with many thanks, Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway … S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13204.xml">letter from R. M. Lloyd, 14 June 1881</ref> and n. 1. A note citing Lloyd for the information about a tame fox licking the hands and face of its master was added to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2401.xml"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, p. 132 n. 12. This edition was edited by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml">Francis Darwin</ref>.</note>
        </div>
    
